@* @foreach over a reassigned Dictionary (BENCH n°44, decision 125): a @foreach over a Dictionary FIELD is
   admitted when that Dict is a signal -- read by the @foreach AND reassigned wholesale. A Dictionary maps to a
   JS Map (decision 118); list() needs an ARRAY, so the source spreads the Map: `() => [...scores.value]` giving
   [[k,v],...]. The loop variable is a KeyValuePair, materialised as a [k,v] pair: @kvp.Key -> kvp[0] (the stable
   reconcile key, static), @kvp.Value -> the REACTIVE lookup scores.value.get(kvp[0]).

   THE VALUE MUST BE REACTIVE. list() REUSES a persisting key's row (it never re-runs create), so a frozen kvp[1]
   would go STALE when that key's value changes, where Blazor re-renders the reused element. This baseline PROVES
   the reactive lookup: scores starts { a=1, b=2 }; #bump reassigns to { b=20, c=3, a=1 } -- key "b" PERSISTS but
   its value changes 2 -> 20, "c" is added, "a" persists, and the order becomes b,c,a. So #list text goes
   "a=1b=2" -> "b=20c=3a=1". Both the value refresh on "b" and the keyed reorder must match Blazor exactly. *@

<ul id="list">
@foreach (KeyValuePair<string, int> kvp in scores)
{
    <li @key="kvp.Key">@kvp.Key=@kvp.Value</li>
}
</ul>

<button id="bump" @onclick="Bump">bump</button>

@code {
    private Dictionary<string, int> scores = new Dictionary<string, int> { { "a", 1 }, { "b", 2 } };

    private void Bump()
    {
        scores = new Dictionary<string, int> { { "b", 20 }, { "c", 3 }, { "a", 1 } };
    }
}
